to 14,, 122 to 188 and 90 to 1200 days,, respectively. There is a non-feedingg prepupal stage of some 8 days andd a pupall perioodd of from 23 to 28 days. Unfavourable climatic or nutritional conditions delay larval development which may be extended up to 144 monthss andd smaller than average sized beetles may be produced. The larva pupates inn a celll constructed by excavating, if inn a log, or by compacting the feeding media, if inn friable materriiaall such as sawdust or compost. Sometiimmeess larvae may also leave a feeding site to pupate inn the earth, andd pupaaee have beenn found as far as 1500 cmm under the ground.
Adult beetleess Ilive for up to six months, durinngg'whichh time they movee betweenn breedingg sites for matingg andd eggg laying, andd feeding sites inn the crowns of palms or on other host plants.
Bothh sexes matee several times andd from studies of spermattoopphhoorree residueess inn the buursaa copul/attrix of fieldd collected females Hoyt (undateedd)) estimatteedd that there is a maximmuumm of eight matings. However, field collectedd females have produceedd fertile eggs upp to 1300 days after beingg confinneedd singly inn cannSs of rottingg sawdust which suggests that multiple matings are not essential. Egggg produccttiioonn varies considerably
- depending on the longevity of the beetle andd the suitability of the oviposition medium. Menoonn and
Pandalai (1958) recorded upp to 152 eggs per female although 90 - 1000 would be moree usual.
Rhinocerrooss beetless are nocturnal creatures, shelterinngg inn the feedingg andd breeding sites during the day and flying inn the hours betweeenn dusk and dawn.. Despittee their large size andd conspicuous appearaannccee they are rarely seenn flying inn plantation areas. Theree is a number of conflicting reports regarddiinngg their flight behaviour. Kalshoovveenn (1951) mentions flights of about 50 metres as normmaall with a potenttiiaall of several hundrreedd metres. Menoonn andd Pandalai (1955B8) state that the beetlee is incapable of extensive flight andd flight ranggee iss restricctteedd to withinn 200 yards of itss breeding place. O'Connoorr (1957)) recordeedd that three rhinoceros beetles hadd flown to lights aboarrdd a ship anchorreedd 7500 yards from landd inn Apia harbour. Hinckley (196677)) demonstrated under laboratory conditions a flight potential of two or three hours for fully fed beetleess tethered on lightweight lines. It would seem, therefore, that under favourable conditions with an abundaannccee of feedingg andd breeding sites short flights are moree usual; longer flights are resortedd to only under adverse conditions.
Damage to palmmss
The larvaee are generally innocuous althouugghh they havee beeenn knownn to damage timber posts and stumpss set into the ground.
Adult beetles feedd at the crowns of palms by boringg through the petiole basbes into the centraall unfolded leaves,. The tissues are macerateedd andd the extracctteedd juices are ingestteedd leavinngg a fibrous frass which Is pushed 'oout through the feeding hole where it lodges as evidence of beetle activity within..
Attackedd palms present a typical appearanccee with accumulations of frasss,, holess or breaks inn petioles andd notches cut inn leaf margins produced by beetles chewing on the unfolddeedd leaflets (Fig. 3). Somettiimmeess the immattuurree spadix at the base of the frondd is damaggeedd thereby directly causinngg a reductiioonn inn the yield of nuts.. If a beetle bores down to the meristemmaattiicc tissue, it may destroy the growing point andd cmonnsequently the palm will diee,. but this is not usuaall inn bearing palms unless attacks are very heavy.. Young palms with a smalll crowwnn are mucchh moree likely to have their growing points damaggeedd or destroyed.
Followwiinngg beetlee attacckk,. palms are exposed to secondary infections from bacteriaa,, fungi or insecttss.. The secondary damage inflictteedd by palm weevils (Rhynchhoopphhoorruuss sppp..)) wherever they occur inn Asia and New ~Guuiineeaa is generally of far more consequencee than rhinoceros beetle attackkss..
Econoommiicc lloosssses
It is extremely difficult to assess the total cost of rhinoceros beetleess to copra producers inn Asia andd the Pacific Islanddss since several componeenntt costs are involvedd,. The first andd most obvious one is the reduceedd yields reflected by lowered copra production.. To this must be addedd the cost of controoll measurreess . which include additionnaall cultural practices which wouldd not have to be undertaken inn the absence of the beetle. Plantation establishmeenntt costs are increaasseedd when re-plantiinng^ must be undertakeenn to replaccee youngg palms destroyed by beetles.. The cost of quarantine procedures designed to limit the spread off the beetle is consideraabbllee even inn unniinnffeesstteedd territories.

