miles) of Niutoputapu in the Kingdoomm of Tonga where the major effort was directed at the destructiioonn of potential breedingg sitess.. Supportingg legislation was enacteedd to compel all adult males on the islandd to providdee free labour for this work. Inn 1930, nearly eight years after itss discoveerryy,, the beetlee had beenn eradicated.
Inn Indiaa and Ceylon, the most important breedinngg sites are inn cattlee dung heaps and pits. Inn South East Asiaa,, decaying logs and sawdust are favouredd breedinngg sites while inn the South Pacific islands most of the breediinngg is inn decaying logs with some inn sawduusstt,, compost andd village rubbisshh heaps.
Where dung heapss and pitss are essential for the mainteennaannccee of agricultural systemss,, they should, idealllyy,, bee covered or screeneedd to prevent beetles gaininngg access but this iss too costly inn most casess,, so an alternative is to turn them at regular intervals and remove any Ofryctes larvae. Sawdust can oftenn be burnt or it may be thinly scattered so that heaps are not allowedd to accumulate,. All too frequently inn control campaignnss,, sawdust heaps are left to become bountifuull breedinngg sites from whence rhinoceros beetles are literallyy 'harveesstteedd'' each time the heaps are searcchheedd,, when for a fraction of the effort which goes into searching for the beetlleess the heapss couldd bee permanently destroyeedd..
Logg dispossaall presents considerable problemmss,, particularly where any large scalee agricuullttuurraall development iss occurring either inn cleariinngg lanndd or destrooyyiinngg oldd palmss inn replanttiinngg schemes.
Where logss cann be stackkeedd andd dried they may bee burnt.. Thiss,, however,, iss not possible inn areass which do not havee a pronounced dry season. Inn Western Samoa,, logs which cannot be burnt arce disposed of by castinngg into the seaa,, (Fig. 4.))..

