Chemical controoll
Chemical controoll measures cann be directed at bothh the larvaaee and adulttss,, but inn botthh casess the cost of labour..a. nd insecticiddeess may bee limitingg factorss inn their adoption as general procedures.
Crown treatment of palms usinngg a 1 :: 9 mixtuurree of 6.5% gamma isomer BHC dust andd sawdust applieedd
to the topmost five axils affords the palmm goodd protectioonn against beetle attack for up to six weeks. How--
ever,, this treatment does not greatly reduuccee the number of beetleess within an area and it seemss that the proteeccttiioonn is due to the repellent effect of the insecticide. Consequently adjacent untreateedd palms may bee moree liable to be attackkeedd by beetleess repellleedd fromm treated palms. Youngg palmss whichh suffer most fromm beetllee attackkss cann be relatively easily treateedd inn this manner but the cost of treatinngg mature palmmss iss prohibitive when climberrss have to bee employed.
O'Connnnoorr (1953) found SBHC and lindane to be more toxic thann dieldrinn against adult beetlleess inn
treated compost and inn a further series of experiimmeennttss., diazinon wettable powder was moree effective than

