BSHHCC,, producing a quickeerr 'knnoocckk dowwnn'' effect and having an effective residual l ife of up to 156 days i n field exposed sawdust mixtuurreess..
Mariau (1967) conducted similar experimentss on an African species of rhinoceros beetllee,, 0O.. monocero 0011..., in which beetles were exposed to insecticide sawdust mixtures. Diazinon was clearly superior to chlorrddaannee,, dieldrinn,, heptachlor and lindane in laboratory testss,, but in field experimmeennttss,, sawdust with BHC and lIiindane proved more effective and more persistent than diazinon granules and sawdust.. BHC was also phytotoxic to young coconut palms.
Inn laboratory screening experimmeennttss,, Stelzerr (1968) found both diazinon and furadan to be more effective than either dieldrin or carbaryl in spray applications against larvae and adults of 00., rhinoceros.
The treatment of beetle breeding sites with insecticides is a practical propositionn only in those situations which are artificially createedd,, e.g.g. . sawdust heapss,, compost pits and possibly in fallen tree trunks and coconut trunks produced by replanting or land development projects. Log and trunk treatment by spraying or injection techniquess has not provedd successful.
Inn the Southh Pacific Regiioonn several coconut replantiinngg schemes are either contemplated or already under way to replace those senile unproductive palms plantedd 50 to 80 years ago by the early Europpeeaann settlers..
The threat to the young replants from beetles breedinngg inn the dead trunks of the old palms is considerable and replanting costs would be greatly reduced if the trunks could be effectively poisoned so that disposal is not necessarryy.. Experiments now being conducted by the U.N.N./S.l.PS.C.P. .C. Project are designed to develop a methoodd to incorporaattee insecticides with silvicides used to thin out senile palms. An additional benefit would be obtainedd if the poisoneedd palmss retainedd their attractiveness as oviposition sites for female beetles but did not permit larvae to complete their development.
Treatment of breeddiinngg sites inn sawdust, cowdung and compost does not present unduuee practicaall difficulty provideedd there are no associatteedd toxicity hazards. Inn many Pacific Islands, domestic poultry and pigs are frequent scavengers inn compost pitss and they are sometimes killeedd following insecticide appllicationss..
Ilnsecticide screeniinngg trials undertaken by the P.LL.. 480 Project inn India indicatedd effective killlss of third instar larvaaee for up to six monthhss after treatment of cowdung with 0.1% BHC, telodrin andd aldrin. Under the same conditionss 0.1%% carbaryll produced 922%%mortality after seven days but after onee montthh it was reducedd to 50%. Under field conditions where weathering is moree severe one wouldd expect the residuall effect to bee somewhat less. Spathhee attack was reducedd from 1322 to 6 per 554 sample palms over an 188 monthss periodd inn ann areaa where alll dungg breeding sites were sprayed four timess per year with 00.01%% carbaryl (Kurian, 1967).
Incluuddeedd amonggsstt chemiiccaall controll methhooddss currently beinngg investigatteedd iss the searchh for attractant chemicals.. Generally thesee mayy bee regaarrddeedd as either sex or feeding anttractaannrtss.. Irnhee eXxiIstence ot a sex attractant has not beeenn demonstrated but data collated inn Westeerrnn Sammooaa by Hinckley (1996677)) showeedd that the incidence off sexually mixxeedd groups of beetles inn breeding sitess was significaannttllyy higher than onee wouldd expect if aggregations were formmeedd by chance encounters.
Conventtiioonnaall methoddss of screening attractannttss by exposing insecttss to the candidaattee chemiccaallss inn olfactometers or cagess have not provveenn successful with O0.. rhiinnoocceerrooss.. The nocttuurrnnaall habits of the beetlee together withh itss large size andd clumsy flight,, evenn inn very large fieldd cages, makkee itt difficult to conduct experimentss whichh willl yieelldd consistenntt results.
Withhiinn thee UU.N../lSS.P.P.C.C. . Project,. a nummbbeerr of chemiccaallss whichh haavvee showwnn promise ass attracttaannttss for scarabaeid beeettlleess inn thee Unitteedd States haavvee beeeenn supplieedd byy thee Uniitteedd Stateess Deppaarrttmmeenntt of Agricultuurree for screeeenniinngg inn direct field exposures too nattuurraall popuullaattiioonnss of thee beetles. Of seveerraall comppoouunnddss whichh havvee exhibited attractant properties, chrysanthemumic aciidd anndd sommee of ittss derivatives seeemm too holldd mosstt promissee (Baarrbbeerr 1967).

